Your structure is much better now. Based on the uploaded directory listing , you've successfully separated the layers into `Shopiy.Api`, `Shopiy.Application`, `Shopiy.Domain`, and `Shopiy.Infrastructure`.

There are still a few things I'd change before implementing the remaining features.

## 1. Create a real solution with four projects (highest priority)

At the moment I only see the folders. Make sure you actually have:

```text
Shopiy.sln

src/
├── Shopiy.Api/
│   └── Shopiy.Api.csproj
├── Shopiy.Application/
│   └── Shopiy.Application.csproj
├── Shopiy.Domain/
│   └── Shopiy.Domain.csproj
└── Shopiy.Infrastructure/
    └── Shopiy.Infrastructure.csproj
```

If all your code is still being compiled by a single `shopiy.csproj`, you're not getting the dependency boundaries that Clean Architecture is intended to provide.

The project references should be:

```text
Shopiy.Api
    ↓
Shopiy.Infrastructure
    ↓
Shopiy.Application
    ↓
Shopiy.Domain
```

---

# 2. Domain

Your Domain layer is almost complete.

```
Domain
├── Common
├── Entities
└── Enums
```

I would add:

```text
Domain
│
├── Constants
│   └── Roles.cs
│
├── ValueObjects
│
└── Events
```

For example:

```csharp
public static class Roles
{
    public const string Admin = "Admin";
    public const string Customer = "Customer";
}
```

Then use `Roles.Admin` instead of `"Admin"` everywhere.

---

